,"category":"politics","header":"Patriot committeeman, then city recorder","body":"A member of Philadelphia’s Committee of Safety from October 1775, Wilcocks served after the war as Recorder of Philadelphia — the officer whose deed-books underpinned the recovering city’s property law. He was a Penn trustee his last twenty-two years."},{"number":2,"category":"business","header":"Twelve thousand acres he never saw","body":"With his father-in-law Benjamin Chew he held forty-three frontier tracts in Somerset and Fayette Counties — nearly 12,000 acres with names like Death of the Fawn and Hunting Lot — run by agents 240 miles from Philadelphia; the partners may never have laid eyes on them. The 1790 division gave Wilcocks 6,011 acres, which his heirs sold off in the Panic of 1837."}],"cross_connections":[{"type":"family_orbit","related_id":"X03302","display_label":"was his father-in-law, law partner, and land partner","link_text":"Judge Benjamin Chew"}],"slug":"alexander-wilcocks-x03304"},"X03305":{"id":"X03305","bio":{"display_name":"Mary Chew Wilcocks","gender":"female"},"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":false,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":false,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"has_descendants_documented":true,"number_of_marriages":1,"tags":[],"sources":[],"birth":{"year":1747},"death":{"year":1794,"month":7,"day":22},"marriages":[{"marriage_number":1,"spouse_id":"X03304","date_year":1768,"date_month":5,"date_day":18,"children_ids":["X03217"]}],"burial":{"cemetery_id":"CEM856"},"parents":{"father_id":"X03302","mother_id":"X03303"},"slug":"mary-chew-wilcocks-x03305"},"X03302":{"id":"X03302","bio":{"display_name":"Judge Benjamin Chew","gender":"male","photo_url":"https://res.cloudinary.com/dc5clrqtw/image/upload/v1781274943/11316238_d1eabcf0-dfe4-42d8-a41a-478d47c6f1c6_crueyy.jpg"},"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":false,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":false,"desce